>>24220170
I think that's why suspense is tricky. There are elements involved, such as the expectations of readers, that either need to weigh on how a writer approaches his/her story or be manipulated and used against readers in appreciable ways. It pays to be aware of popular tropes/pitfalls and how to avoid or use them, too. I'm not at all dismissing the criticality of tone and avoiding whiplash, though; to that point, I think it's important to ensure that a story always maintains a near-constant drip of the mood it's intended to convey. When I inquired about this earlier, I more intended to find out if the thread can handle a story that gets really bumpy but still has a clear silver lining, or a light at the end of its darkest parts. I don't want to punish anyone that decides to read it. I like satisfying endings; the bigger the struggle, the better the potential that its conclusion can be written well enough to include readers in the triumph of its characters and just what that feels like.

>>24220378
